 992, "end": 995}}, {"id": ["mesh:D001120"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "L-arginine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.999433696269989, "span": {"begin": 1014, "end": 1024}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013481"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "superoxide", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9998409748077393, "span": {"begin": 1039, "end": 1049}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009569"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "nitric oxide", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9993051290512085, "span": {"begin": 1102, "end": 1114}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:30158"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "BH4", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9989047050476074, "span": {"begin": 1150, "end": 1153}}, {"id": ["mesh:D014652"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "vascular diseases", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9771786332130432, "span": {"begin": 1193, "end": 1210}}, {"id": ["mesh:D006973"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hypertension", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999887943267822, "span": {"begin": 1219, "end": 1231}}, {"id": ["mesh:D003920"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "diabetes", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999775886535645, "span": {"begin": 1233, "end": 1241}}, {"id": ["mim:108725", "mesh:D050197"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "atherosclerosis", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999961853027344, "span": {"begin": 1246, "end": 1261}}, {"id": ["mesh:D010900"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "endothelial dysfunction", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9977084994316101, "span": {"begin": 1268, "end": 1291}}], "text": "Tetrahydrobiopterin (BH4) is an essential cofactor for a group of enzymes including aromatic acid hydroxylases, nitric oxide synthase (NOS) isoforms, and alkylglycerol monooxygenase (Wang et al., 2014). BH4 is synthesized from guanosine triphosphate through sequential reactions catalyzed by enzymes GTPCH-1, pyruvoyl tetrahydropterin synthase, and sepiapterin reductase (Tatham et al., 2009). During NOS catalysis, BH4 donates electrons to the ferrous-dioxygen complex in the oxygenase domain, leading to oxidation of L-arginine to N-hydroxy-Larginine and eventually conversion to citrulline and nitric oxide production (Chen et al., 2011; Crabtree et al., 2009). BH4 also stabilizes dimers of NOS isoforms, which is required for their enzymatic activity. When BH4 levels are decreased or limited, for example under oxidative stress conditions, BH4 can be oxidized to dihydrobiopterin (BH2) and then converted to biopterin. This reduction in BH4 availability results in NOS uncoupling where NOS is uncoupled from L-arginine oxidation and superoxide (or other reactive species) is produced rather than nitric oxide (Carnicer et al., 2012). Decreased BH4 have been demonstrated in a variety of vascular diseases such as hypertension, diabetes and atherosclerosis where endothelial dysfunction occurs.", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:38:07 +0000 2026"}